Problem 3.1

The UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository6 contains a data set related to glass identification. The data consist of 214 glass samples labeled as one of seven class categories. There are nine predictors, including the refractive index and percentages of eight elements: Na, Mg, Al, Si, K, Ca, Ba, and Fe.

(a) Using visualizations, explore the predictor variables to understand their distributions as well as the relationships between predictors.

Using a simple describe( ) function we can see that there are som variables we will need to take closer looks at, with RI, Mg, K, Ca, Ba and Fe appearing skewed based on this table, and also RI, Na, Si, K , Ca,Ba and to a lesser extent Fe with some challenging tail shapes (kurtosis != 3.0)

Skew of Numeric Variables

This can also be done using the package e1071:

require(e1071)
skewer<-function(df){
    for(name in colnames(df)){
    skew <-skewness(df[,name])
    print(paste(colnames(df[name]),": ", skew))}
}

skewer(Glass[, 1:9])

Looking at Histograms visually illustrates the challenges with these distributions.

require(caret)
require(corrplot)
#3.1


hist_plotter<-function(df){
    names_list = colnames(df)
    for (name in names_list){
        if (is.numeric(df[[name]])){
        hist(df[[name]],
             breaks = 30,
             main = paste0('Distribution of ', name, ' Variable'),
             col ='darkorchid',
             xlab=name)
            }
    }
    
}

hist_plotter(Glass)

Correleations Between Numeric Glass Variables

glassCor <- cor(Glass[-10])
corrplot(glassCor, method = "square", type = "lower")

There is some significant positive corelation between Ca and RI as well as bit less between Ba and Al, as well as Ba and Na and K and Al,

There is some obvious negative correlations betweeen Si and RI as well as Al and RI, Al and Mg, Ca and Mg as well as Ba and Mg.

(b) Do there appear to be any outliers in the data?

Yes, there are outliers in several variables, RI, Na,K, Ca and Fe all have outliers past their contiguous right bounds which are visible in the histograms.

Are any predictors skewed?
Yes, Mg is bimodal and Ba, K and Fe are right skewed, while the remaining variables are not really normal, they are both Leptokurtic and Platykurtic to some extent, but centrally tending.

This would suggest looking at the skew values as well as some possible transformations down the line might be of use!

(c) Are there any relevant transformations of one or more predictors that might improve the classification model?

A simple log transformation does seem to show improvements in the distribution of the iron variable Fe, however it does introduce some outliers on the left, and all the zero values of Fe go to -Inf and are not reflected at all in this distribution .

Evaluating these histograms, there is marginal improvement in most of the variables, the only one with notable afffirmative changes is Ca. Given the commoness of outliers in this data set as well as skew, it maight be useful to try a spatialSign() transformation.

trans <- preProcess(Glass, method = c('center', 'scale', 'spatialSign'))

trans_glass <- predict(trans, Glass)

3.2.

The soybean data can also be found at the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository. Data were collected to predict disease in 683 soybeans. The 35 predictors are mostly categorical and include information on the environmental conditions (e.g., temperature, precipitation) and plant conditions (e.g., left spots, mold growth). The outcome labels consist of 19 distinct classes. 6 http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/index.html.

prop_isna  <- function(col){
    knitr::kable(prop.table(table(is.na(col))))
}

prop_tabler  <- function(col){
    knitr::kable(prop.table(table(col)))

(c) Develop a strategy for handling missing data, either by eliminating predictors or imputation.

There is no simple method of handling missing data in this data set AND preserving the global utility of the data. Because the classes with missing data have many incomplete variables in the observations, any for of imputation which might be useful in the less empty classes would introduce a lot of error into those 5 classes.

If some form of imputation (MICE is my go-to package) it would be important to create another variable for each imputed variable that was a 0 1 flag indicating whether or not that variable was imputed for that observation. This would allow models with high sensistivity to this sort of handling to use the native values differently than the imputed values by attributing the bias to the flag variable. I have used this in logistic regression models with some success. It may also be useful to use a PCA to or LDA to extract the most variance in a smaller sample of the variables.

It could be useful to simply purge the most empty 4 (or 5 ) classes and move forward with imputation on the rest. or to remove the 4 emptiest classes, establish which variables are most important using PCA, then see how those variables are represented by the 4 fragile classes with high NA countsif theh are less impacted, it might be possible to impute across the remaining variables for all classes using flags for imputed values and preserve a pretty high level of predictive power.
